Calibrating a DHT22 sensor typically involves comparing its readings to a reference (like another calibrated sensor or instrument) and then making adjustments to the readings to improve accuracy. Here's an example code for calibrating a DHT22 sensor using an Arduino. You'll need the "DHT.h" library installed, which you can get from the Arduino Library Manager in the Arduino IDE.

```cpp
#include "DHT.h"

#define DHTPIN 2         // Define the pin connected to the DHT22 sensor
#define DHTTYPE DHT22    // Define the sensor type (DHT22)

DHT dht(DHTPIN, DHTTYPE);

// Calibration factors (adjust these values based on your reference sensor or instrument)
float temperatureCalibrationFactor = 1.0;
float humidityCalibrationFactor = 1.0;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600); // Start the serial communication at 9600 baud rate
  dht.begin();        // Initialize the DHT22 sensor
}

void loop() {
  delay(2000); // Wait for 2 seconds to ensure stable sensor readings

  float calTemperature = dht.readTemperature() * temperatureCalibrationFactor;
  float calHumidity = dht.readHumidity() * humidityCalibrationFactor;

  if (isnan(calTemperature) || isnan(calHumidity)) { // Check if any value is NaN
    Serial.println("Failed to read from DHT22 sensor!");
    return;
  }

  Serial.print("Calibrated Temperature: ");
  Serial.print(calTemperature);
  Serial.print("°C ");
  Serial.print("  ");
  Serial.print("Calibrated Humidity: ");
  Serial.print(calHumidity);
  Serial.println("%");
}
```

Replace `temperatureCalibrationFactor` and `humidityCalibrationFactor` variables with the calibration factors based on your reference. These factors can be calculated by comparing the DHT22 sensor's readings to a known reference sensor or instrument.

